  "prompt": "Why do I have to tip the server?",
  "response": "Tipping servers in restaurants is a customary practice in many countries, particularly in the United States. Here are some reasons why tipping is generally expected:\n\n1. **Income Supplement**: In many places, servers earn a base wage that is below the minimum wage because tips are expected to make up the difference. Tipping helps ensure that servers earn a livable income.\n\n2. **Service Recognition**: Tipping is a way to reward good service. If a server provides excellent service, a tip is a way to show appreciation and acknowledge their efforts.\n\n3. **Cultural Norms**: Tipping is ingrained in the dining culture of certain countries. In the U.S., for example, it is considered part of the dining experience. Not tipping can be seen as a breach of social etiquette.\n\n4. **Motivation**: Tips can motivate servers to provide better service. Knowing that their income can directly be affected by the quality of service they provide can incentivize them to ensure customers have a positive experience.\n\n5. **Economic Reality**: Many restaurants rely on the tipping system to keep labor costs low. This allows them to price their menu items more competitively. Without tips, restaurants might need to raise prices to pay higher wages.\n\nIt\u2019s important to note that tipping customs can vary greatly from country to country. In some places, service charges are included in the bill, or tipping is not customary at all. Understanding local customs and practices can help you navigate dining experiences in different regions.",
